## GIA vs IGI for Loose Cushion Cut Diamonds

Two labs. Different standards.

**GIA** is stricter. A stone GIA grades G-VS1 might get F-VVS2 from IGI. GIA costs more — usually 5–15% extra. For natural diamonds, always buy GIA.

**IGI** is the standard for lab-grown. Most lab cushions are IGI-certified. Widely accepted. Great prices. For lab diamonds, IGI Ideal is the right call.

Simple rule: natural = GIA. Lab = IGI Ideal.

Why does GIA cost more? Because GIA grades harder. A stone that gets G-VS1 from GIA might get F-VVS2 from IGI. So GIA stones carry a premium — you're paying for the stricter eye. For natural diamonds, that premium is worth it. Resale, trust, long-term value — GIA is the standard.

For lab-grown, IGI is what most vendors use. It's accepted everywhere. The grading is good. And lab diamonds don't hold value the same way natural ones do, so the GIA premium matters less. Go IGI Ideal and spend the difference on more carats.

---

## Loose Cushion Cut Diamond vs Pre-Set Ring

Should you buy loose or pre-set? Here's how to decide.

**Buy loose if:**
- You want to pick the exact stone yourself
- You have a specific setting in mind
- Budget matters — loose + setting is almost always cheaper
- You want the full grading certificate for the stone alone

**Buy pre-set if:**
- You want everything done in one order
- You don't want to manage two purchases
- The design is unique and hard to replicate

The price almost always favors loose. Pre-set rings add 20–40% on top of the stone price for the setting. On a [$13,679 2ct cushion](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29359194?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), that's a real number.

Think about it this way: a $13,679 loose 2ct cushion modified in a $900 platinum setting = $14,579 total. The same stone pre-set might run $17,000–$19,000. Same ring. You saved $2,500–$4,500 by buying loose and choosing your own setting. That savings buys a very good platinum band with room to spare.

---

## Elongated Loose Cushion Cut Diamond

The elongated cushion has a length-to-width ratio above 1.15. It looks longer and narrower than a square cushion. More like an oval, but with cushion faceting. Makes fingers look longer on the hand.

Square cushions are everywhere. Elongated cushions are harder to find loose. You'll need to search specifically.

Look at the GIA measurements in millimeters. Divide the longer side by the shorter side. That gives you the L/W ratio. Aim for 1.15–1.30 for the elongated look.

See the full [elongated cushion cut diamond guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond) for L/W ratio breakdowns and specific picks.

---

## Fancy Color Loose Cushion Cut Diamonds

Cushion cuts aren't just for white diamonds. Yellow and pink loose cushions exist — and the prices are completely different.

**Loose yellow cushion:** Natural Fancy Yellow starts around [$1,549 per carat](/yellow-cushion-cut-diamond). Fancy Intense and Fancy Vivid grades climb fast. Lab yellow cushions cost a fraction of natural. Full guide: [yellow cushion cut diamond](/yellow-cushion-cut-diamond).

**Loose pink cushion:** Natural Fancy Brownish Pink starts at [$9,488 for 1ct](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond). Fancy Intense Purplish Pink reaches nearly $1M for 1ct. Lab pink cushion starts at [$3,045 for 5ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond). Full guide: [pink cushion cut diamond](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond).

For fancy color cushions, buying loose matters even more. Color saturation varies stone to stone even at the same GIA grade. You need to see the actual stone on video before you decide.

Two GIA Fancy Yellow cushions with identical certificates can look completely different face-up. One reads as a rich, saturated yellow. The other looks pale. Same grade on paper. The video tells the real story. This is true for pink too. Never buy a fancy color cushion without video. For natural pink especially, request video in multiple lighting conditions — daylight, indoor, and a single light source over the stone.

---

## What to Look for When Buying a Loose Cushion Cut Diamond

The 4Cs on the certificate are just the start. Four more things matter for cushion cuts — and none of them are on the report.

**Length-to-width ratio.** The GIA report lists measurements in millimeters. Divide long side by short side. 1.00–1.05 = square. 1.10–1.20 = slightly elongated. 1.20+ = elongated cushion. Decide your preference before you search.

**Faceting pattern.** The certificate doesn't tell you crushed ice vs chunky facets. Only video shows this. Always watch the HD video. Photos lie.

**Table percentage.** 55–65% table gives the best light. Above 70% spreads the stone but hurts brightness. Ask the vendor if it's not listed.

**Fluorescence.** Strong blue fluorescence can look hazy outdoors in bright sun. Inside, it's usually fine. I recommend none-to-faint for most buyers. Medium-blue on G–H color is okay if the video looks clean.

**Return policy.** Minimum 30 days. No exceptions. You need to see the stone in the setting under real light before you commit. If a vendor won't give you 30 days, walk away.

One more thing: check the actual return process. Some vendors say "30 days" but make you jump through hoops to actually return. Read the policy page before you order. Make sure it covers loose stones, not just pre-set rings. Some policies exclude loose diamonds in the fine print.

---

## How to Set a Loose Cushion Cut Diamond

You have three options after you buy the stone.

**Local jeweler.** Bring the stone in. Get a setting quote. Most local jewelers have catalogs with hundreds of setting options — not just what's in their case. Cheapest route. You can inspect the work before you pay.

**Online setting vendor.** Buy the stone and setting from the same place. They set it and ship the finished ring. Easy. Confirm cushion size compatibility before ordering.

**Custom jeweler.** If you have a specific design in mind, a custom jeweler builds the setting around your exact stone. Most expensive. Takes 3–6 weeks. Give them the GIA report with measurements at the start.

For prong count: four prongs show more of the stone. Six prongs hold it more securely — worth it above 2ct.

A halo makes the stone look bigger. A solitaire lets the cushion be the main event. Pavé band adds sparkle on the sides without touching the center.

Not sure about the setting? Buy the stone first. The stone decision is where your money goes. The setting can wait.

A loose diamond can sit safely in its original holder for weeks or months. There's no rush to set it immediately. Use that time to think about the design. Talk to a local jeweler. Look at settings in person. You've already locked in the stone at a good price — the setting decision has no deadline.

---

## Cushion Modified Brilliant vs Standard Cushion — Which to Buy?

Most online certified inventory is cushion modified brilliant. That's just how the market is now. But cushion brilliant still exists, and it's worth knowing the difference.

- **Want lots of sparkle everywhere?** Cushion modified. The crushed-ice look. Bright and busy.
- **Want big, bold flashes?** Cushion brilliant. Old-mine style. More dramatic under a single light.
- **Taking a lot of photos?** Cushion modified photographs brighter.
- **Wearing in candlelight or low light?** Cushion brilliant shows up beautifully.

Neither is better. It's a personal preference. Make the decision loose, with an HD video, before the stone is set.

