## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is a loose cushion cut diamond?
A loose cushion cut diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond sold on its own — no setting, no ring. Just the stone with a GIA or IGI certificate. That certificate lists the cut, color, clarity, carat, fluorescence, and exact measurements. You buy the stone first, then pick your setting separately.

The "loose" part means the stone hasn't been set into anything yet. It's just the diamond, in a small plastic holder or a box. You can hold it, look at it, watch it under different lights, compare it to another stone. That's the point. Buying loose is how you make a real decision instead of guessing.

### How much does a loose cushion cut diamond cost?
Natural GIA: from [$1,891 for 1ct G-VS1 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab IGI: from [$1,422 for 1.5ct E-VVS2](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Price goes up with carat, color, clarity, and which lab certified it.

### Is a loose cushion cut diamond cheaper than a round?
Yes. By a lot. A 1ct GIA round G-VS2 is [$3,230](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090690?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). A 1ct GIA cushion G-VS1 is [$1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). That's 41% less. Same quality. Different shape. Fewer people want cushion, so the price is lower. If you like the shape, that's your win.

### What is the difference between cushion modified brilliant and cushion brilliant?
Cushion modified brilliant = crushed ice. Lots of tiny flashes everywhere. Modern. Bright. Cushion brilliant = bigger facets. Fewer flashes. Bolder look. More vintage. Most certified loose cushions today are cushion modified. If you want cushion brilliant, you need to search for it specifically.

### What is a loose cushion cut diamond price at 2 carats?
Natural GIA: from [$13,679 for F-VVS2 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29359194?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab IGI: from [$2,606 for D-VVS1 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The lab 2ct is the best value in this whole dataset.

### What is a loose cushion cut diamond price at 3 carats?
Natural GIA: from [$32,692 for G-VVS2 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961123?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab GIA: from [$5,962 for D-VVS1 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Three carats lab for under $6,000. That's the most striking price in certified loose diamonds right now.

### Should I buy a loose cushion cut or a pre-set ring?
Buy loose almost every time. You see the exact stone. You control the setting choice. You usually pay less. The only reason to go pre-set is convenience — or if the design you want is hard to build separately.

The math is simple. A [$1,891 loose cushion](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) plus an $800 setting = $2,691. The same stone pre-set in a branded ring often runs $3,200–$3,800. You're paying $500–$1,100 for the convenience of one click. For most buyers, that's not worth it.

### What color grade is best for a loose cushion cut diamond?
G. It looks white in any setting. D costs $2,500 more at 1ct for no visible difference. F adds $150–$200 for nothing you can see. Stop at G.

### What clarity is eye-clean in a loose cushion cut diamond?
VS2 is safe in any cushion. VS1 is overkill. SI1 is often eye-clean in cushion modified brilliant — all those tiny facets hide inclusions well. Always watch the HD video for SI1. SI2 is risky above 1ct. Don't buy it without expert review.

Why does cushion modified hide inclusions better? Because the crushed-ice faceting pattern breaks up the view inside the stone. In a round brilliant, light travels in predictable paths — inclusions can appear more clearly. In a cushion modified, light bounces everywhere. The inclusion gets lost in the sparkle. This is a real advantage for clarity-conscious buyers on a budget.

### GIA or IGI for loose cushion cut diamond?
Natural stone: GIA only. GIA is stricter and more trusted worldwide. Lab-grown: IGI Ideal is the right choice — lower price, well-accepted, great value. GIA-certified lab cushions exist and cost more; worth it if resale matters to you.

### What is an elongated loose cushion cut diamond?
It's a cushion cut with a length-to-width ratio above 1.15. Looks longer and narrower than a square cushion. More like an oval with cushion faceting. Makes fingers look longer. Harder to find loose. Search by GIA measurements in millimeters to find your exact ratio. Full details in the [elongated cushion cut guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond).

### How do I buy a loose cushion cut diamond safely?
Use a vendor that has HD video for every stone. Watch it before you buy. Check the GIA or IGI certificate number on the lab's website — takes 30 seconds. Confirm the L/W ratio from the measurements. For lab stones, check the growth method on the certificate. Make sure the return window is at least 30 days. No video? No 30-day return? Walk away.

### Can I buy a loose yellow or pink cushion cut diamond?
Yes. Natural yellow cushion cuts start around $1,549/ct for Fancy Yellow. Lab yellow cushions cost much less. Natural pink starts at $9,488 for 1ct Fancy Brownish Pink. Lab pink cushion starts at $3,045 for 5ct Fancy Vivid Pink. See the full guides: [yellow cushion cut diamond](/yellow-cushion-cut-diamond) and [pink cushion cut diamond](/pink-cushion-cut-diamond).

### What is cushion modified brilliant?
It's GIA's name for the crushed-ice cushion style. Lots of small facets. Lots of tiny flashes. It's the most common type of cushion cut loose diamond in certified inventory. The other type — cushion brilliant — has bigger facets and fewer, bolder flashes. Both are real GIA-certified diamonds. The difference is in how they sparkle.
